SIMPLE: intellect
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intellect
<hw>In"tel*lect</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intellectus</ets>, fr. <ets>intelligere</ets>,
<ets>intellectum</ets>, to understand: cf. <ets>intellect</ets>. See
<er>Intelligent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>The
part or faculty of the human mind by which it knows, as distinguished
from the power to feel and to will; the power to judge and comprehend;
the thinking faculty; the understanding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The capacity for higher forms of knowledge, as
distinguished from the power to perceive objects in their relations;
mental capacity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A particular mind, especially a person of high
intelligence; <as>as, he was a great <ex>intellect</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intellected</ent>⟦br⟧
